[src:gcp-dataflow/apache-beam] Apache Beam is one implementation of the Dataflow model paper.
[src:gcp-dataflow/apache-beam] The Dataflow model is based on previous work on distributed processing abstractions at Google, in particular on FlumeJava and Millwheel.
[src:gcp-dataflow/apache-beam] Google released an open SDK implementation of the Dataflow model in 2014 and an environment to execute Dataflows locally (non-distributed) as well as in the Google Cloud Platform service.
[src:gcp-dataflow/apache-beam] Apache Beam makes minor releases every 6 weeks.
[src:gcp-dataflow/batch-processing] In computing, **batch processing** is the running of a software job in an automated and unattended way.
[src:gcp-dataflow/batch-processing] A user schedules a job to run and then waits for a processing system to run it.
[src:gcp-dataflow/batch-processing] Typically, a job is scheduled to run at a configured time of day or when an event occurs or when computer resources are available.
[src:gcp-dataflow/batch-processing] The term "batch processing" originates in the traditional classification of methods of production as job production (one-off production), batch production (production of a "batch" of multiple items at once, one stage at a time), and flow production (mass production, all stages in process at once).
[src:gcp-dataflow/batch-processing] Early computers were capable of running only one program at a time.
[src:gcp-dataflow/batch-processing] Each user had sole control of the machine for a scheduled period of time.
[src:gcp-dataflow/batch-processing] They would arrive at the computer with program and data, often on punched paper cards and magnetic or paper tape, and would load their program, run and debug it, and carry off their output when done.
[src:gcp-dataflow/batch-processing] As computers became faster the setup and takedown time became a larger percentage of available computer time.
[src:gcp-dataflow/batch-processing] Programs called *monitors*, the forerunners of operating systems, were developed which could process a series, or "batch", of programs, often from magnetic tape prepared offline.
[src:gcp-dataflow/batch-processing] The monitor would be loaded into the computer and run the first job of the batch.
[src:gcp-dataflow/batch-processing] At the end of the job it would regain control and load and run the next until the batch was complete.
[src:gcp-dataflow/batch-processing] Often the output of the batch would be written to magnetic tape and printed or punched offline.
[src:gcp-dataflow/batch-processing] Examples of monitors were IBM's *Fortran Monitor System*, SOS (Share Operating System), and finally IBSYS for IBM's 709x systems in 1960.
[src:gcp-dataflow/batch-processing] Third-generation computers capable of multiprogramming began to appear in the 1960s.
[src:gcp-dataflow/batch-processing] Instead of running one batch job at a time, these systems can have multiple batch programs running at the same time in order to keep the system as busy as possible.
[src:gcp-dataflow/batch-processing] One or more programs might be awaiting input, one actively running on the CPU, and others generating output.
[src:gcp-dataflow/batch-processing] Instead of offline input and output, programs called spoolers read jobs from cards, disk, or remote terminals and place them in a job queue to be run.
[src:gcp-dataflow/batch-processing] In order to prevent deadlocks the job scheduler needs to know each job's resource requirements—memory, magnetic tapes, mountable disks, etc., so various scripting languages were developed to supply this information in a structured way.
[src:gcp-dataflow/batch-processing] Probably the most well-known is IBM's *Job Control Language* (JCL).
[src:gcp-dataflow/batch-processing] Job schedulers select jobs to run according to a variety of criteria, including priority, memory size, etc.
[src:gcp-dataflow/batch-processing] Remote batch is a procedure for submitting batch jobs from remote terminals, often equipped with a punch card reader and a line printer.
[src:gcp-dataflow/batch-processing] Sometimes asymmetric multiprocessing is used to spool batch input and output for one or more large computers using an attached smaller and less-expensive system, as in the IBM System/360 Attached Support Processor.
[src:gcp-dataflow/batch-processing] The first general-purpose time-sharing system, Compatible Time-Sharing System (CTSS), was compatible with batch processing.
[src:gcp-dataflow/batch-processing] This facilitated transitioning from batch processing to interactive computing.
[src:gcp-dataflow/batch-processing] From the late 1960s onwards, interactive computing such as via text-based computer terminal interfaces (as in Unix shells or read-eval-print loops), and later graphical user interfaces became common.
[src:gcp-dataflow/batch-processing] Non-interactive computation, both one-off jobs such as compilation, and processing of multiple items in batches, became retrospectively referred to as *batch processing*, and the term *batch job* (in early use often "batch *of* jobs") became common.
[src:gcp-dataflow/batch-processing] Early use is particularly found at the University of Michigan, around the Michigan Terminal System (MTS).
[src:gcp-dataflow/batch-processing] Although timesharing did exist, its use was not robust enough for corporate data processing; none of this was related to the earlier unit record equipment, which was human-operated.
[src:gcp-dataflow/batch-processing] Non-interactive computation remains widespread in computing, both for general data processing and for system "housekeeping" tasks (using system software).
[src:gcp-dataflow/batch-processing] A high-level program (executing multiple programs, with some additional "glue" logic) is today most often called a *script*, and written in scripting languages, particularly shell scripts for system tasks; in IBM PC DOS and MS-DOS this is instead known as a batch file.
[src:gcp-dataflow/batch-processing] That includes UNIX-based computers, Microsoft Windows, macOS (whose foundation is the BSD Unix kernel), and even smartphones.
[src:gcp-dataflow/batch-processing] A running script, particularly one executed from an interactive login session, is often known as a job, but that term is used very ambiguously.
[src:gcp-dataflow/batch-processing] "There is no direct counterpart to z/OS batch processing in PC or UNIX systems.
[src:gcp-dataflow/batch-processing] Batch jobs are typically executed at a scheduled time or on an as-needed basis.
[src:gcp-dataflow/batch-processing] Batch applications are still critical in most organizations in large part because many common business processes are amenable to batch processing.
[src:gcp-dataflow/batch-processing] While online systems can also function when manual intervention is not desired, they are not typically optimized to perform high-volume, repetitive tasks.
[src:gcp-dataflow/batch-processing] Therefore, even new systems usually contain one or more batch applications for updating information at the end of the day, generating reports, printing documents, and other non-interactive tasks that must complete reliably within certain business deadlines.
[src:gcp-dataflow/batch-processing] Some applications are amenable to flow processing, namely those that only need data from a single input at once (not totals, for instance): start the next step for each input as it completes the previous step.
[src:gcp-dataflow/batch-processing] In this case flow processing lowers latency for individual inputs, allowing them to be completed without waiting for the entire batch to finish.
[src:gcp-dataflow/batch-processing] However, many applications require data from all records, notably computations such as totals.
[src:gcp-dataflow/batch-processing] In this case the entire batch must be completed before one has a usable result: partial results are not usable.
[src:gcp-dataflow/batch-processing] Modern batch applications make use of modern batch frameworks such as Jem The Bee, Spring Batch or implementations of JSR 352 written for Java, and other frameworks for other programming languages, to provide the fault tolerance and scalability required for high-volume processing.
[src:gcp-dataflow/batch-processing] In order to ensure high-speed processing, batch applications are often integrated with grid computing solutions to partition a batch job over a large number of processors, although there are significant programming challenges in doing so.
[src:gcp-dataflow/batch-processing] High volume batch processing places particularly heavy demands on system and application architectures as well.
[src:gcp-dataflow/batch-processing] Architectures that feature strong input/output performance and vertical scalability, including modern mainframe computers, tend to provide better batch performance than alternatives.
[src:gcp-dataflow/batch-processing] Scripting languages became popular as they evolved along with batch processing.
[src:gcp-dataflow/batch-processing] A *batch window* is "a period of less-intensive online activity", when the computer system is able to run batch jobs without interference from, or with, interactive online systems.
[src:gcp-dataflow/batch-processing] A bank's *end-of-day (EOD)* jobs require the concept of *cutover*, where transaction and data are cut off for a particular day's batch activity ("deposits after 3 PM will be processed the next day").
[src:gcp-dataflow/batch-processing] As requirements for online systems uptime expanded to support globalization, the Internet, and other business needs, the batch window shrank and increasing emphasis was placed on techniques that would require online data to be available for a maximum amount of time.
[src:gcp-dataflow/batch-processing] The *batch size* refers to the number of work units to be processed within one batch operation.
[src:gcp-dataflow/batch-processing] The IBM mainframe z/OS operating system or platform has arguably the most highly refined and evolved set of batch processing facilities owing to its origins, long history, and continuing evolution.
[src:gcp-dataflow/batch-processing] Today such systems commonly support hundreds or even thousands of concurrent online and batch tasks within a single operating system image.
[src:gcp-dataflow/batch-processing] The Unix programs `cron`, `at`, and `batch` (today `batch` is a variant of `at`) allow for complex scheduling of jobs.
[src:gcp-dataflow/batch-processing] Most high-performance computing clusters use batch processing to maximize cluster usage.
[src:gcp-dataflow/dataflow-programming] In computer programming, **dataflow programming** is a programming paradigm that models a program as a directed graph of the data flowing between operations, thus implementing dataflow principles and architecture.
[src:gcp-dataflow/dataflow-programming] Dataflow programming languages share some features of functional languages, and were generally developed in order to bring some functional concepts to a language more suitable for numeric processing.
[src:gcp-dataflow/dataflow-programming] Some authors use the term *datastream* instead of *dataflow* to avoid confusion with dataflow computing or dataflow architecture, based on an indeterministic machine paradigm.
[src:gcp-dataflow/dataflow-programming] Dataflow programming was pioneered by Jack Dennis and his graduate students at MIT in the 1960s.
[src:gcp-dataflow/dataflow-programming] Traditionally, a program is modelled as a series of operations happening in a specific order; this may be referred to as sequential, procedural, control flow (indicating that the program chooses a specific path), or imperative programming.
[src:gcp-dataflow/dataflow-programming] The program focuses on commands, in line with the von Neumann vision of sequential programming, where data is normally "at rest".
[src:gcp-dataflow/dataflow-programming] In contrast, dataflow programming emphasizes the movement of data and models programs as a series of connections.
[src:gcp-dataflow/dataflow-programming] Explicitly defined inputs and outputs connect operations, which function like black boxes.
[src:gcp-dataflow/dataflow-programming] An operation runs as soon as all of its inputs become valid.
[src:gcp-dataflow/dataflow-programming] Thus, dataflow languages are inherently parallel and can work well in large, decentralized systems.
[src:gcp-dataflow/dataflow-programming] One of the key concepts in computer programming is the idea of state, essentially a snapshot of various conditions in the system.
[src:gcp-dataflow/dataflow-programming] Most programming languages require a considerable amount of state information, which is generally hidden from the programmer.
[src:gcp-dataflow/dataflow-programming] Often, the computer itself has no idea which piece of information encodes the enduring state.
[src:gcp-dataflow/dataflow-programming] This is a serious problem, as the state information needs to be shared across multiple processors in parallel processing machines.
[src:gcp-dataflow/dataflow-programming] Most languages force the programmer to add extra code to indicate which data and parts of the code are important to the state.
[src:gcp-dataflow/dataflow-programming] This code tends to be both expensive in terms of performance, as well as difficult to read or debug.
[src:gcp-dataflow/dataflow-programming] Explicit parallelism is one of the main reasons for the poor performance of Enterprise Java Beans when building data-intensive, non-OLTP applications.
[src:gcp-dataflow/dataflow-programming] Where a sequential program can be imagined as a single worker moving between tasks (operations), a dataflow program is more like a series of workers on an assembly line, each doing a specific task whenever materials are available.
[src:gcp-dataflow/dataflow-programming] Since the operations are only concerned with the availability of data inputs, they have no hidden state to track, and are all "ready" at the same time.
[src:gcp-dataflow/dataflow-programming] Dataflow programs are represented in different ways.
[src:gcp-dataflow/dataflow-programming] A traditional program is usually represented as a series of text instructions, which is reasonable for describing a serial system which pipes data between small, single-purpose tools that receive, process, and return.
[src:gcp-dataflow/dataflow-programming] Dataflow programs start with an input, perhaps the command line parameters, and illustrate how that data is used and modified.
[src:gcp-dataflow/dataflow-programming] The flow of data is explicit, often visually illustrated as a line or pipe.
[src:gcp-dataflow/dataflow-programming] In terms of encoding, a dataflow program might be implemented as a hash table, with uniquely identified inputs as the keys, used to look up pointers to the instructions.
[src:gcp-dataflow/dataflow-programming] When any operation completes, the program scans down the list of operations until it finds the first operation where all inputs are currently valid, and runs it.
[src:gcp-dataflow/dataflow-programming] When that operation finishes, it will typically output data, thereby making another operation become valid.
[src:gcp-dataflow/dataflow-programming] For parallel operation, only the list needs to be shared; it is the state of the entire program.
[src:gcp-dataflow/dataflow-programming] Thus the task of maintaining state is removed from the programmer and given to the language's runtime.
[src:gcp-dataflow/dataflow-programming] On machines with a single processor core where an implementation designed for parallel operation would simply introduce overhead, this overhead can be removed completely by using a different runtime.
[src:gcp-dataflow/dataflow-programming] Some recent dataflow libraries such as Differential/Timely Dataflow have used incremental computing for much more efficient data processing.
[src:gcp-dataflow/dataflow-programming] A pioneer dataflow language was BLOck DIagram (BLODI), published in 1961 by John Larry Kelly, Jr., Carol Lochbaum and Victor A.
[src:gcp-dataflow/dataflow-programming] Vyssotsky for specifying sampled data systems.
[src:gcp-dataflow/dataflow-programming] A BLODI specification of functional units (amplifiers, adders, delay lines, etc.) and their interconnections was compiled into a single loop that updated the entire system for one clock tick.
[src:gcp-dataflow/dataflow-programming] In a 1966 Ph.D. thesis, *The On-line Graphical Specification of Computer Procedures*, Bert Sutherland created one of the first graphical dataflow programming frameworks in order to make parallel programming easier.
[src:gcp-dataflow/dataflow-programming] Subsequent dataflow languages were often developed at the large supercomputer labs.
[src:gcp-dataflow/dataflow-programming] SISAL, a popular dataflow language developed at Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory, looks like most statement-driven languages, but variables should be assigned once.
[src:gcp-dataflow/dataflow-programming] This allows the compiler to easily identify the inputs and outputs.
[src:gcp-dataflow/dataflow-programming] A number of offshoots of SISAL have been developed, including SAC, *Single Assignment C*, which tries to remain as close to the popular C programming language as possible.
[src:gcp-dataflow/dataflow-programming] The United States Navy funded development of signal processing graph notation (SPGN) and ACOS starting in the early 1980s.
[src:gcp-dataflow/dataflow-programming] This is in use on a number of platforms in the field today.
[src:gcp-dataflow/dataflow-programming] A more radical concept is Prograph, in which programs are constructed as graphs onscreen, and variables are replaced entirely with lines linking inputs to outputs.
[src:gcp-dataflow/dataflow-programming] Prograph was originally written on the Macintosh, which remained single-processor until the introduction of the DayStar Genesis MP in 1996.
[src:gcp-dataflow/dataflow-programming] There are many hardware architectures oriented toward the efficient implementation of dataflow programming models.
[src:gcp-dataflow/dataflow-programming] MIT's tagged token dataflow architecture was designed by Greg Papadopoulos.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] The model is a specialization of the *split-apply-combine* strategy for data analysis.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] It is inspired by the map and reduce functions commonly used in functional programming, although their purpose in the MapReduce framework is not the same as in their original forms.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] As such, a single-threaded implementation of MapReduce is usually not faster than a traditional (non-MapReduce) implementation; any gains are usually only seen with multi-threaded implementations on multi-processor hardware.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] The use of this model is beneficial only when the optimized distributed shuffle operation (which reduces network communication cost) and fault tolerance features of the MapReduce framework come into play.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] Optimizing the communication cost is essential to a good MapReduce algorithm.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] MapReduce libraries have been written in many programming languages, with different levels of optimization.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] A popular open-source implementation that has support for distributed shuffles is part of Apache Hadoop.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] The name MapReduce originally referred to the proprietary Google technology, but has since become a generic trademark.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] By 2014, Google was no longer using MapReduce as its primary *big data* processing model, and development on Apache Mahout had moved on to more capable and less disk-oriented mechanisms that incorporated full map and reduce capabilities.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] Processing can occur on data stored either in a filesystem (unstructured) or in a database (structured).
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] MapReduce can take advantage of the locality of data, processing it near the place it is stored in order to minimize communication overhead.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] **Shuffle:** worker nodes redistribute data based on the output keys (produced by the `map` function), such that all data belonging to one key is located on the same worker node.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] **Reduce:** worker nodes now process each group of output data, per key, in parallel.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] MapReduce allows for the distributed processing of the map and reduction operations.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] Maps can be performed in parallel, provided that each mapping operation is independent of the others; in practice, this is limited by the number of independent data sources and/or the number of CPUs near each source.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] Similarly, a set of 'reducers' can perform the reduction phase, provided that all outputs of the map operation that share the same key are presented to the same reducer at the same time, or that the reduction function is associative.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] The parallelism also offers some possibility of recovering from partial failure of servers or storage during the operation: if one mapper or reducer fails, the work can be rescheduled – assuming the input data are still available.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] **Run the user-provided Map() code** – Map() is run exactly once for each *K1* key, generating output organized by key *K2*.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] **"Shuffle" the Map output to the Reduce processors** – the MapReduce system designates Reduce processors, assigns the *K2* key each processor should work on, and provides that processor with all the Map-generated data associated with that key.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] **Run the user-provided Reduce() code** – Reduce() is run exactly once for each *K2* key produced by the Map step.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] **Produce the final output** – the MapReduce system collects all the Reduce output, and sorts it by *K2* to produce the final outcome.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] These five steps can be logically thought of as running in sequence – each step starts only after the previous step is completed – although in practice they can be interleaved as long as the final result is not affected.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] In many situations, the input data might have already been distributed ("sharded") among many different servers, in which case step 1 could sometimes be greatly simplified by assigning Map servers that would process the locally present input data.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] Similarly, step 3 could sometimes be sped up by assigning Reduce processors that are as close as possible to the Map-generated data they need to process.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] The *Map* and *Reduce* functions of *MapReduce* are both defined with respect to data structured in (key, value) pairs.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] The *Map* function is applied in parallel to every pair (keyed by `k1`) in the input dataset.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] This produces a list of pairs (keyed by `k2`) for each call.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] After that, the MapReduce framework collects all pairs with the same key (`k2`) from all lists and groups them together, creating one group for each key.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] Each *Reduce* call typically produces either one key value pair or an empty return, though one call is allowed to return more than one key value pair.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] The returns of all calls are collected as the desired result list.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] Thus the MapReduce framework transforms a list of (key, value) pairs into another list of (key, value) pairs.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] This behavior is different from the typical functional programming map and reduce combination, which accepts a list of arbitrary values and returns one single value that combines *all* the values returned by map.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] It is necessary but not sufficient to have implementations of the map and reduce abstractions in order to implement MapReduce.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] Distributed implementations of MapReduce require a means of connecting the processes performing the Map and Reduce phases.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] Other options are possible, such as direct streaming from mappers to reducers, or for the mapping processors to serve up their results to reducers that query them.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] Here, each document is split into words, and each word is counted by the *map* function, using the word as the result key.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] The framework puts together all the pairs with the same key and feeds them to the same call to *reduce*.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] Thus, this function just needs to sum all of its input values to find the total appearances of that word.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] As another example, imagine that for a database of 1.1 billion people, one would like to compute the average number of social contacts a person has according to age.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] Note that in the Reduce function, C is the count of people having in total N contacts, so in the Map function it is natural to write C=1, since every output pair is referring to the contacts of one single person.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] The MapReduce system would line up the 1100 Map processors, and would provide each with its corresponding 1 million input records.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] The Map step would produce 1.1 billion (Y,(N,1)) records, with Y values ranging between, say, 8 and 103.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] The MapReduce System would then line up the 96 Reduce processors by performing shuffling operation of the key/value pairs due to the fact that we need average per age, and provide each with its millions of corresponding input records.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] The Reduce step would result in the much reduced set of only 96 output records (Y,A), which would be put in the final result file, sorted by Y.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] The count info in the record is important if the processing is reduced more than one time.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] If we reduce it with file #3, we lose the count of how many records we've already seen, so we end up with an average of 9.5 contacts for a 10-year-old person ((9+10)/2), which is wrong.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] Software framework architecture adheres to open-closed principle where code is effectively divided into unmodifiable *frozen spots* and extensible *hot spots*.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] The frozen spot of the MapReduce framework is a large distributed sort.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] The *input reader* divides the input into appropriate size 'splits' (in practice, typically, 64 MB to 128 MB) and the framework assigns one split to each *Map* function.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] The *input reader* reads data from stable storage (typically, a distributed file system) and generates key/value pairs.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] A common example will read a directory full of text files and return each line as a record.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] The *Map* function takes a series of key/value pairs, processes each, and generates zero or more output key/value pairs.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] The input and output types of the map can be (and often are) different from each other.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] If the application is doing a word count, the map function would break the line into words and output a key/value pair for each word.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] Each output pair would contain the word as the key and the number of instances of that word in the line as the value.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] Each *Map* function output is allocated to a particular *reducer* by the application's *partition* function for sharding purposes.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] The *partition* function is given the key and the number of reducers and returns the index of the desired *reducer*.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] A typical default is to hash the key and use the hash value modulo the number of *reducers*.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] Between the map and reduce stages, the data are *shuffled* (parallel-sorted / exchanged between nodes) in order to move the data from the map node that produced them to the shard in which they will be reduced.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] The shuffle can sometimes take longer than the computation time depending on network bandwidth, CPU speeds, data produced and time taken by map and reduce computations.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] The input for each *Reduce* is pulled from the machine where the *Map* ran and sorted using the application's *comparison* function.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] The framework calls the application's *Reduce* function once for each unique key in the sorted order.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] The *Reduce* can iterate through the values that are associated with that key and produce zero or more outputs.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] In the word count example, the *Reduce* function takes the input values, sums them and generates a single output of the word and the final sum.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] The *Output Writer* writes the output of the *Reduce* to the stable storage.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] Properties of monoids are the basis for ensuring the validity of MapReduce operations.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] In the Algebird package a Scala implementation of Map/Reduce explicitly requires a monoid class type .
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] The operations of MapReduce deal with two types: the type *A* of input data being mapped, and the type *B* of output data being reduced.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] The *Map* operation takes individual values of type *A* and produces, for each *a:A* a value *b:B*; The *Reduce* operation requires a binary operation • defined on values of type *B*; it consists of folding all available *b:B* to a single value.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] From a basic requirements point of view, any MapReduce operation must involve the ability to arbitrarily regroup data being reduced.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] The second property guarantees that, when parallelized over multiple nodes, the nodes that don't have any data to process would have no impact on the result.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] These two properties amount to having a monoid (*B*, •, *e*) on values of type *B* with operation • and with neutral element *e*.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] There's no requirements on the values of type *A*; an arbitrary function *A* → *B* can be used for the *Map* operation.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] This means that we have a catamorphism *A** → (*B*, •, *e*).
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] Here *A** denotes a Kleene star, also known as the type of lists over *A*.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] The *Shuffle* operation per se is not related to the essence of MapReduce; it's needed to distribute calculations over the cloud.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] It follows from the above that not every binary *Reduce* operation will work in MapReduce.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] MapReduce programs are not guaranteed to be fast.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] The main benefit of this programming model is to exploit the optimized shuffle operation of the platform, and only having to write the *Map* and *Reduce* parts of the program.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] In practice, the author of a MapReduce program however has to take the shuffle step into consideration; in particular the partition function and the amount of data written by the *Map* function can have a large impact on the performance and scalability.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] Additional modules such as the *Combiner* function can help to reduce the amount of data written to disk, and transmitted over the network.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] MapReduce applications can achieve sub-linear speedups under specific circumstances.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] When designing a MapReduce algorithm, the author needs to choose a good tradeoff between the computation and the communication costs.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] Communication cost often dominates the computation cost, and many MapReduce implementations are designed to write all communication to distributed storage for crash recovery.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] In tuning performance of MapReduce, the complexity of mapping, shuffle, sorting (grouping by the key), and reducing has to be taken into account.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] The amount of data produced by the mappers is a key parameter that shifts the bulk of the computation cost between mapping and reducing.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] Reducing includes sorting (grouping of the keys) which has nonlinear complexity.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] Hence, small partition sizes reduce sorting time, but there is a trade-off because having a large number of reducers may be impractical.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] The influence of split unit size is marginal (unless chosen particularly badly, say <1MB).
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] The gains from some mappers reading load from local disks, on average, is minor.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] For processes that complete quickly, and where the data fits into main memory of a single machine or a small cluster, using a MapReduce framework usually is not effective.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] Since these frameworks are designed to recover from the loss of whole nodes during the computation, they write interim results to distributed storage.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] This crash recovery is expensive, and only pays off when the computation involves many computers and a long runtime of the computation.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] A task that completes in seconds can just be restarted in the case of an error, and the likelihood of at least one machine failing grows quickly with the cluster size.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] On such problems, implementations keeping all data in memory and simply restarting a computation on node failures or —when the data is small enough— non-distributed solutions will often be faster than a MapReduce system.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] MapReduce achieves reliability by parceling out a number of operations on the set of data to each node in the network.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] Each node is expected to report back periodically with completed work and status updates.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] If a node falls silent for longer than that interval, the master node (similar to the master server in the Google File System) records the node as dead and sends out the node's assigned work to other nodes.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] Individual operations use atomic operations for naming file outputs as a check to ensure that there are not parallel conflicting threads running.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] When files are renamed, it is possible to also copy them to another name in addition to the name of the task (allowing for side-effects).
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] The reduce operations operate much the same way.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] Because of their inferior properties with regard to parallel operations, the master node attempts to schedule reduce operations on the same node, or in the same rack as the node holding the data being operated on.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] This property is desirable as it conserves bandwidth across the backbone network of the datacenter.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] Implementations are not necessarily highly reliable.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] For example, in older versions of Hadoop the *NameNode* was a single point of failure for the distributed filesystem.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] Moreover, the MapReduce model has been adapted to several computing environments like multi-core and many-core systems, desktop grids, multi-cluster, volunteer computing environments, dynamic cloud environments, mobile environments, and high-performance computing environments.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] At Google, MapReduce was used to completely regenerate Google's index of the World Wide Web.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] It replaced the old *ad hoc* programs that updated the index and ran the various analyses.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] Development at Google has since moved on to technologies such as Percolator, FlumeJava and MillWheel that offer streaming operation and updates instead of batch processing, to allow integrating "live" search results without rebuilding the complete index.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] MapReduce's stable inputs and outputs are usually stored in a distributed file system.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] The transient data are usually stored on local disk and fetched remotely by the reducers.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] David DeWitt and Michael Stonebraker, computer scientists specializing in parallel databases and shared-nothing architectures, have been critical of the breadth of problems that MapReduce can be used for.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] They called its interface too low-level and questioned whether it really represents the paradigm shift its proponents have claimed it is.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] They challenged the MapReduce proponents' claims of novelty, citing Teradata as an example of prior art that has existed for over two decades.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] Greg Jorgensen wrote an article rejecting these views.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] Jorgensen asserts that DeWitt and Stonebraker's entire analysis is groundless as MapReduce was never designed nor intended to be used as a database.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] DeWitt and Stonebraker have subsequently published a detailed benchmark study in 2009 comparing performance of Hadoop's MapReduce and RDBMS approaches on several specific problems.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] They concluded that relational databases offer real advantages for many kinds of data use, especially on complex processing or where the data is used across an enterprise, but that MapReduce may be easier for users to adopt for simple or one-time processing tasks.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] The MapReduce programming paradigm was also described in Danny Hillis's 1985 thesis intended for use on the Connection Machine, where it was called "xapping/reduction" and relied upon that machine's special hardware to accelerate both map and reduce.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] The dialect ultimately used for the Connection Machine, the 1986 StarLisp, had parallel `*map` and `reduce!!`, which in turn was based on the 1984 Common Lisp, which had non-parallel `map` and `reduce` built in.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] The tree-like approach that the Connection Machine's hypercube architecture uses to execute `reduce` in $O(\log n)$ time is effectively the same as the approach referred to within the Google paper as prior work.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] In 2010 Google was granted what is described as a patent on MapReduce.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] The patent, filed in 2004, may cover use of MapReduce by open source software such as Hadoop, CouchDB, and others.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] In *Ars Technica*, an editor acknowledged Google's role in popularizing the MapReduce concept, but questioned whether the patent was valid or novel.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] In 2013, as part of its "Open Patent Non-Assertion (OPN) Pledge", Google pledged to only use the patent defensively.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] The patent is expected to expire on 23 December 2026.
[src:gcp-dataflow/mapreduce] MapReduce tasks must be written as acyclic dataflow programs, i.e. a stateless mapper followed by a stateless reducer, that are executed by a batch job scheduler.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] In computer science, **stream processing** (also known as **event stream processing**, **data stream processing**, or **distributed stream processing**) is a programming paradigm which views streams, or sequences of events in time, as the central input and output objects of computation.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] Stream processing encompasses dataflow programming, reactive programming, and distributed data processing.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] Stream processing systems use streaming algorithms to trace parallel processing for data streams.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] The stream processing paradigm simplifies parallel software and hardware by restricting the parallel computation that can be performed.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] Given a sequence of data (a *stream*), a series of operations (*kernel functions*) is applied to each element in the stream.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] Kernel functions are usually pipelined, and optimal local on-chip memory reuse is attempted, in order to minimize the loss in bandwidth, associated with external memory interaction.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] *Uniform streaming*, where one kernel function is applied to all elements in the stream, is typical.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] Since the kernel and stream abstractions expose data dependencies, compiler tools can fully automate and optimize on-chip management tasks.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] Stream processing hardware can use scoreboarding, for example, to initiate a direct memory access (DMA) when dependencies become known.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] The elimination of manual DMA management reduces software complexity, and an associated elimination for hardware cached I/O, reduces the data area expanse that has to be involved with service by specialized computational units such as arithmetic logic units.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] During the 1980s stream processing was explored within dataflow programming.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] An example is the language SISAL (Streams and Iteration in a Single Assignment Language).
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] Stream processing is essentially a compromise, driven by a data-centric model that works very well for traditional DSP or GPU-type applications (such as image, video and digital signal processing) but less so for general purpose processing with more randomized data access (such as databases).
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] By sacrificing some flexibility in the model, the implications allow easier, faster and more efficient execution.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] Depending on the context, processor design may be tuned for maximum efficiency or a trade-off for flexibility.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] For each record we can only read from the input, perform operations on it, and write to the output.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] It is permissible to have multiple inputs and multiple outputs, but never a piece of memory that is both readable and writable.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] By way of illustration, the following code fragments demonstrate detection of patterns within event streams.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] The first is an example of processing a data stream using a continuous SQL query (a query that executes forever processing arriving data based on timestamps and window duration).
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] This code fragment illustrates a JOIN of two data streams, one for stock orders, and one for the resulting stock trades.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] The query outputs a stream of all Orders matched by a Trade within one second of the Order being placed.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] The output stream is sorted by timestamp, in this case, the timestamp from the Orders stream.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] Another sample code fragment detects weddings among a flow of external "events" such as church bells ringing, the appearance of a man in a tuxedo or morning suit, a woman in a flowing white gown and rice flying through the air.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] A "complex" or "composite" event is what one infers from the individual simple events: a wedding is happening.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] Basic computers started from a sequential execution paradigm.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] Traditional CPUs are SISD based, which means they conceptually perform only one operation at a time.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] As the computing needs of the world evolved, the amount of data to be managed increased very quickly.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] It was obvious that the sequential programming model could not cope with the increased need for processing power.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] Various efforts have been spent on finding alternative ways to perform massive amounts of computations but the only solution was to exploit some level of parallel execution.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] The result of those efforts was SIMD, a programming paradigm which allowed applying one instruction to multiple instances of (different) data.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] Most of the time, SIMD was being used in a SWAR environment.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] By using more complicated structures, one could also have MIMD parallelism.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] Although those two paradigms were efficient, real-world implementations were plagued with limitations from memory alignment problems to synchronization issues and limited parallelism.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] Only few SIMD processors survived as stand-alone components; most were embedded in standard CPUs.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] Consider a simple program adding up two arrays containing 100 4-component vectors (i.e.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] This is the sequential paradigm that is most familiar.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] Variations do exist (such as inner loops, structures and such), but they ultimately boil down to that construct.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] It assumes the instruction `vector_sum` works.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] Although this is what happens with instruction intrinsics, much information is actually not taken into account here such as the number of vector components and their data format.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] You can see however, this method reduces the number of decoded instructions from *numElements * componentsPerElement* to *numElements*.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] The number of jump instructions is also decreased, as the loop is run fewer times.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] These gains result from the parallel execution of the four mathematical operations.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] What happened however is that the packed SIMD register holds a certain amount of data so it's not possible to get more parallelism.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] The speed up is somewhat limited by the assumption we made of performing four parallel operations (please note this is common for both AltiVec and SSE).
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] In this paradigm, the whole dataset is defined, rather than each component block being defined separately.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] Describing the set of data is assumed to be in the first two rows.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] After that, the result is inferred from the sources and kernel.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] For simplicity, there's a 1:1 mapping between input and output data but this does not need to be.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] Applied kernels can also be much more complex.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] An implementation of this paradigm can "unroll" a loop internally.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] This allows throughput to scale with chip complexity, easily utilizing hundreds of ALUs.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] The elimination of complex data patterns makes much of this extra power available.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] While stream processing is a branch of SIMD/MIMD processing, they must not be confused.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] Although SIMD implementations can often work in a "streaming" manner, their performance is not comparable: the model envisions a very different usage pattern which allows far greater performance by itself.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] It has been noted that when applied on generic processors such as standard CPU, only a 1.5x speedup can be reached.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] By contrast, ad-hoc stream processors easily reach over 10x performance, mainly attributed to the more efficient memory access and higher levels of parallel processing.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] Although there are various degrees of flexibility allowed by the model, stream processors usually impose some limitations on the kernel or stream size.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] For example, consumer hardware often lacks the ability to perform high-precision math, lacks complex indirection chains or presents lower limits on the number of instructions which can be executed.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] Stanford University stream processing projects included the Stanford Real-Time Programmable Shading Project started in 1999.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] A prototype called Imagine was developed in 2002.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] A project called Merrimac ran until about 2004.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] AT&T also researched stream-enhanced processors as graphics processing units rapidly evolved in both speed and functionality.[1] Since these early days, dozens of stream processing languages have been developed, as well as specialized hardware.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] The most immediate challenge in the realm of parallel processing does not lie as much in the type of hardware architecture used, but in how easy it will be to program the system in question in a real-world environment with acceptable performance.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] Machines like Imagine use a straightforward single-threaded model with automated dependencies, memory allocation and DMA scheduling.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] This in itself is a result of the research at MIT and Stanford in finding an optimal *layering of tasks* between programmer, tools and hardware.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] Programmers beat tools in mapping algorithms to parallel hardware, and tools beat programmers in figuring out smartest memory allocation schemes, etc.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] Of particular concern are MIMD designs such as Cell, for which the programmer needs to deal with application partitioning across multiple cores and deal with process synchronization and load balancing.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] A drawback of SIMD programming was the issue of array-of-structures (AoS) and structure-of-arrays (SoA).
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] When multiple of these structures exist in memory they are placed end to end creating an arrays in an *array of structures* (AoS) topology.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] This means that should some algorithm be applied to the location of each particle in turn it must skip over memory locations containing the other attributes.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] If these attributes are not needed this results in wasteful usage of the CPU cache.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] Additionally, a SIMD instruction will typically expect the data it will operate on to be contiguous in memory, the elements may also need to be aligned.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] By moving the memory location of the data out of the structure data can be better organised for efficient access in a stream and for SIMD instructions to operate one.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] A *structure of arrays* (SoA), as shown below, can allow this.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] Instead of holding the data in the structure, it holds only pointers (memory locations) for the data.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] Shortcomings are that if multiple attributes to of an object are to be operated on they might now be distant in memory and so result in a cache miss.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] The aligning and any needed padding lead to increased memory usage.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] Overall, memory management may be more complicated if structures are added and removed for example.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] For stream processors, the usage of structures is encouraged.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] From an application point of view, all the attributes can be defined with some flexibility.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] Taking GPUs as reference, there is a set of attributes (at least 16) available.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] For each attribute, the application can state the number of components and the format of the components (but only primitive data types are supported for now).
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] The various attributes are then attached to a memory block, possibly defining a *stride* between 'consecutive' elements of the same attributes, effectively allowing interleaved data.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] When the GPU begins the stream processing, it will *gather* all the various attributes in a single set of parameters (usually this looks like a structure or a "magic global variable"), performs the operations and *scatters* the results to some memory area for later processing (or retrieving).
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] More modern stream processing frameworks provide a FIFO like interface to structure data as a literal stream.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] This abstraction provides a means to specify data dependencies implicitly while enabling the runtime/hardware to take full advantage of that knowledge for efficient computation.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] One of the simplest and most efficient stream processing modalities to date for C++, is RaftLib, which enables linking independent compute kernels together as a data flow graph using C++ stream operators.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] Apart from specifying streaming applications in high-level languages, models of computation (MoCs) also have been widely used as dataflow models and process-based models.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] Historically, CPUs began implementing various tiers of memory access optimizations because of the ever-increasing performance when compared to relatively slow growing external memory bandwidth.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] As this gap widened, big amounts of die area were dedicated to hiding memory latencies.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] Since fetching information and opcodes to those few ALUs is expensive, very little die area is dedicated to actual mathematical machinery (as a rough estimation, consider it to be less than 10%).
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] A similar architecture exists on stream processors but thanks to the new programming model, the amount of transistors dedicated to management is actually very little.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] Beginning from a whole system point of view, stream processors usually exist in a controlled environment.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] GPUs do exist on an add-in board (this seems to also apply to Imagine).
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] CPUs continue do the job of managing system resources, running applications, and such.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] The stream processor is usually equipped with a fast, efficient, proprietary memory bus (crossbar switches are now common, multi-buses have been employed in the past).
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] The exact amount of memory lanes is dependent on the market range.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] As this is written, there are still 64-bit wide interconnections around (entry-level).
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] Most mid-range models use a fast 128-bit crossbar switch matrix (4 or 2 segments), while high-end models deploy huge amounts of memory (actually up to 512 MB) with a slightly slower crossbar that is 256 bits wide.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] By contrast, standard processors from Intel Pentium to some Athlon 64 have only a single 64-bit wide data bus.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] Memory access patterns are much more predictable.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] While arrays do exist, their dimension is fixed at kernel invocation.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] The thing which most closely matches a multiple pointer indirection is an *indirection chain*, which is however guaranteed to finally read or write from a specific memory area (inside a stream).
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] Because of the SIMD nature of the stream processor's execution units (ALUs clusters), read/write operations are expected to happen in bulk, so memories are optimized for high bandwidth rather than low latency (this is a difference from Rambus and DDR SDRAM, for example).
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] This also allows for efficient memory bus negotiations.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] Most (90%) of a stream processor's work is done on-chip, requiring only 1% of the global data to be stored to memory.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] This is where knowing the kernel temporaries and dependencies pays.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] Internally, a stream processor features some clever communication and management circuits but what's interesting is the *Stream Register File* (SRF).
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] This is conceptually a large cache in which stream data is stored to be transferred to external memory in bulks.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] As a cache-like software-controlled structure to the various ALUs, the SRF is shared between all the various ALU clusters.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] The key concept and innovation here done with Stanford's Imagine chip is that the compiler is able to automate and allocate memory in an optimal way, fully transparent to the programmer.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] The dependencies between kernel functions and data is known through the programming model which enables the compiler to perform flow analysis and optimally pack the SRFs.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] Commonly, this cache and DMA management can take up the majority of a project's schedule, something the stream processor (or at least Imagine) totally automates.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] Tests done at Stanford showed that the compiler did an as well or better job at scheduling memory than if you hand tuned the thing with much effort.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] There is proof; there can be a lot of clusters because inter-cluster communication is assumed to be rare.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] Internally however, each cluster can efficiently exploit a much lower amount of ALUs because intra-cluster communication is common and thus needs to be highly efficient.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] To keep those ALUs fetched with data, each ALU is equipped with local register files (LRFs), which are basically its usable registers.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] This three-tiered data access pattern, makes it easy to keep temporary data away from slow memories, thus making the silicon implementation highly efficient and power-saving.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] Although an order of magnitude speedup can be reasonably expected (even from mainstream GPUs when computing in a streaming manner), not all applications benefit from this.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] Communication latencies are actually the biggest problem.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] Although PCI Express improved this with full-duplex communications, getting a GPU (and possibly a generic stream processor) to work will possibly take long amounts of time.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] This means it's usually counter-productive to use them for small datasets.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] Because changing the kernel is a rather expensive operation the stream architecture also incurs penalties for small streams, a behaviour referred to as the *short stream effect*.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] Pipelining is a very widespread and heavily used practice on stream processors, with GPUs featuring pipelines exceeding 200 stages.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] The cost for switching settings is dependent on the setting being modified but it is now considered to always be expensive.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] To avoid those problems at various levels of the pipeline, many techniques have been deployed such as "über shaders" and "texture atlases".
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] Those techniques are game-oriented because of the nature of GPUs, but the concepts are interesting for generic stream processing as well.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] Most programming languages for stream processors start with Java, C or C++ and add extensions which provide specific instructions to allow application developers to tag kernels and/or streams.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] This also applies to most shading languages, which can be considered stream programming languages to a certain degree.
[src:gcp-dataflow/stream-processing] Commercial implementations are either general purpose or tied to specific hardware by a vendor.
[src:gcp-dataflow/watermark-data-synchronization] This approach allows the client to retrieve only the objects which have changed since the latest watermark, and also enables the client to resume its synchronization job from where it left off in the event of some pause or downtime.
